# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-valiant-vk
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] The rule replaced the previous rule ADR27 (introduced 1 September 1973), and remained in effect until replaced by ADR37/00 (introduced 1 July 1988).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] The rule was endorsed by the Australian Transport Advisory Council (ATAC), and covered all Australian states and territories.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] Vehicles required to comply with ADR27A were mostly passenger vehicles and light goods vehicles based upon passenger vehicles manufactured on or after 1 July 1976.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] *Table 1* defines those which were required to comply with or were exempt from the rule.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] The rule was updated to allow greater deterioration factors for vehicles manufactured on or after 1 January 1978.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] Prior to the release of a new model, manufacturers were required to submit a certain number of new vehicles for testing for each different engine available across a specific model's range.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] The number of vehicles required for testing depended upon expected production volumes.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] Only those models which passed compliance testing were eligible for sale to be driven on Australian public roads.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] The rule required manufacturers to introduce emission control systems to the engines of road-registered vehicles on sale within Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] In some cases, manufacturers were also required to modify the engines of these vehicles, mostly in the areas of cylinder heads, camshafts, carburettors and ignitions systems to meet the "cleaner" requirements.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] As a result, ADR27A-compliant engines generally produced less power than previous non-compliant versions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] The rule prohibited the commercial importation of vehicles manufactured outside of Australia that did not comply with the rule, or the modification or supplying of alternate engines to vehicles manufactured or sold in Australia that would result in vehicles no longer complying with the requirements.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] Where vehicles were privately imported or engines modified, they had to be inspected and certified by an authorised compliance engineer.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/adr27a] Vehicles that failed testing, or compliance testing had not been undertaken, were deemed unroadworthy and penalties and/or bans applied (usually varying from state to state) if the vehicles were driven on public roads.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] A **car**, or an **automobile**, is a motor vehicle with wheels.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Most definitions of cars state that they run primarily on roads, seat 1-8 people, have four wheels, and mainly transport people rather than cargo.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] There are over 1.6 billion cars in use worldwide as of 2025.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The French inventor Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot built the first steam-powered road vehicle in 1769, while the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed and constructed the first internal combustion-powered automobile in 1808.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The modern car—a practical, marketable automobile for everyday use—was invented in 1886, when the German inventor Carl Benz patented his Benz Patent-Motorwagen.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Commercial cars became widely available during the 20th century.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The 1901 Oldsmobile Curved Dash and the 1908 Ford Model T, both American cars, are widely considered the first mass-produced and mass-affordable cars, respectively.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Cars were rapidly adopted in the US, where they replaced horse-drawn carriages.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In Europe and other parts of the world, demand for automobiles did not increase until after World War II.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In the 21st century, car usage is still increasing rapidly, especially in China, India, and other newly industrialised countries.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Cars have controls for driving, parking, passenger comfort, and a variety of lamps.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Over the decades, additional features and controls have been added to vehicles, making them progressively more complex.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] These include rear-reversing cameras, air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Most cars in use in the early 2020s are propelled by an internal combustion engine, fueled by the combustion of fossil fuels.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Electric cars, which were invented early in the history of the car, became commercially available in the 2000s and widespread in the 2020s.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The transition from fossil-fuel-powered cars to electric cars is a central feature of most climate change mitigation scenarios.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] There are costs and benefits to car use.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The costs to the individual include acquiring the vehicle, interest payments (if the car is financed), repairs and maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The costs to society include resources used to produce cars and fuel, maintaining roads, land-use, road congestion, air pollution, noise pollution, public health, and disposing of the vehicle at the end of its life.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Traffic collisions are the largest cause of injury-related deaths worldwide.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Personal benefits include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Societal benefits include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation from the automotive industry, transportation provision, and societal wellbeing from leisure and travel opportunities.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] People's ability to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for society.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The English word *car* is believed to originate from Latin *carrus*/*carrum* "wheeled vehicle" or (via Old North French) Middle English **carre** "two-wheeled cart", both of which in turn derive from Gaulish **karros** "chariot".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] It originally referred to any wheeled horse-drawn vehicle, such as a cart, carriage, or wagon.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The word also occurs in other Celtic languages.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] "Motor car", attested from 1895, is the usual formal term in British English.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] "Autocar", a variant likewise attested from 1895 and literally meaning "self-propelled car", is now considered archaic.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] "Horseless carriage" is attested from 1895.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] "Automobile", a classical compound derived from Ancient Greek **autós** (αὐτός) "self" and Latin **mobilis** "movable", entered English from French and was first adopted by the Automobile Club of Great Britain in 1897.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] It fell out of favour in Britain and is now used chiefly in North America, where the abbreviated form "auto" commonly appears as an adjective in compound formations like "auto industry" and "auto mechanic".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1649, Hans Hautsch of Nuremberg built a clockwork-driven carriage.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The first steam-powered vehicle was designed by Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish member of a Jesuit mission in China around 1672.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] It was a 65-centimetre-long (26 in) scale-model toy for the Kangxi Emperor that was unable to carry a driver or a passenger.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] It is not known with certainty if Verbiest's model was successfully built or run.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot is widely credited with building the first full-scale, self-propelled mechanical vehicle in about 1769; he created a steam-powered tricycle.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] He also constructed two steam tractors for the French Army, one of which is preserved in the French National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] His inventions were limited by problems with water supply and maintaining steam pressure.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1801, Richard Trevithick built and demonstrated his Puffing Devil road locomotive, believed by many to be the first demonstration of a steam-powered road vehicle.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] It was unable to maintain sufficient steam pressure for long periods and was of little practical use.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The development of external combustion (also known as steam) engines is detailed in the history of the car.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Still, it is often treated separately from the development of cars in their modern understanding.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] A variety of steam-powered road vehicles were used during the first part of the 19th century, including steam cars, steam buses, phaetons, and steam rollers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In the United Kingdom, sentiment against them led to the Locomotive Acts of 1865.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1807, Nicéphore Niépce and his brother Claude created what was probably the world's first internal combustion engine (which they called a Pyréolophore), but installed it in a boat on the river Saone in France.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Coincidentally, in 1807, the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed his own "de Rivaz internal combustion engine", and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to be powered by such an engine.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The Niépces' Pyréolophore was fuelled by a mixture of Lycopodium powder (dried spores of the Lycopodium plant), finely crushed coal dust, and resin that were mixed with oil, whereas de Rivaz used a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Neither design was successful, as was the case with others, such as Samuel Brown, Samuel Morey, and Etienne Lenoir, who each built vehicles (usually adapted carriages or carts) powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In November 1881, French inventor Gustave Trouvé demonstrated a three-wheeled car powered by electricity at the International Exposition of Electricity.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Several other German engineers, including Gottlieb Daimler, Wilhelm Maybach, Siegfried Marcus, and Carl Benz were also working on cars and engines at about the same time.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1879, Benz was granted a patent for a stationary engine.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] He had long dreamed of applying the internal combustion engine to produce a horseless carriage and began work on it in 1884.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1885 he produced his first prototype car, the Benz Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] On 29 January 1886 he applied for a patent for it, which was granted on 2 November of that year.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Benz further developed the Patent-Motorwagen, and had sufficient confidence in this to drive into Mannheim and have his vehicle written up in the *Neue Badische Landeszeitung* of 4 June 1886.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Benz' first production car, the Patent-Motorwagen Model 2, was produced in single-digit numbers in 1887–88.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Frenchman Émile Roger, already producing Benz engines under license, had added the Benz car to his product line in 1888.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Perhaps 60 of the Model 3 were produced between 1889 and 1893, the majority assembled in Paris from kits by Émile Roger.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Many historians consider Benz' advances so significant that they largely credit him as the inventor of the car and regard his 1886 patent as the birth of the modern car.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In August 1888, Bertha Benz, the wife and business partner of Carl Benz, undertook the first road trip by an internal combustion engine car, to prove the road-worthiness of her husband's invention.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1896, Carl Benz designed and patented the first internal-combustion flat engine, called *boxermotor*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] During the last years of the 19th century, Benz was the largest car company in the world with 572 units produced in 1899 and, because of its size, Benz & Cie. became a joint-stock company.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The first motor car in central Europe and one of the first factory-made cars in the world was produced by the Czech company Nesselsdorfer Wagenbau (later renamed to Tatra) in 1897, the Präsident automobil.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Daimler and Maybach founded Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft (DMG) in Cannstatt in 1890, and sold their first car in 1892 under the brand name *Daimler*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] It was a horse-drawn stagecoach built by another manufacturer, which they retrofitted with an engine of their design.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] By 1895, about 30 vehicles had been built by Daimler and Maybach, either at the Daimler works or at the Hotel Hermann, where they set up shop after disputes with their backers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Benz, Maybach, and the Daimler team seem to have been unaware of each other's early work.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] They never worked together; by the time of the merger of the two companies, Daimler and Maybach were no longer part of DMG.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Daimler died in 1900, and later that year, Maybach designed an engine named *Daimler-Mercedes* that was installed in a specially ordered model built to specifications set by Emil Jellinek.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] This was a limited production run of vehicles for Jellinek to race and market in his country.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Two years later, in 1902, a new model of the DMG car was produced and named Mercedes after the Maybach engine, which generated 35 hp.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Maybach left DMG shortly thereafter and opened his own business.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Rights to the *Daimler* brand name were sold to other manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1890, Émile Levassor (who had bought a Benz Patent-Motorwagen Model 2 in 1888) and Armand Peugeot of France began producing vehicles with Daimler engines, and so laid the foundation of the automotive industry in France.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1891, Auguste Doriot and his Peugeot colleague Louis Rigoulot completed the longest trip by a petrol-driven vehicle when their self-designed and built Daimler-powered Peugeot Type 3 completed 2,100 kilometres (1,300 mi) from Valentigney to Paris and Brest and back again.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] They were attached to the first Paris–Brest–Paris bicycle race, but finished six days after the winning cyclist, Charles Terront.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The first design for an American car with a petrol internal combustion engine was made in 1877 by George Selden of Rochester, New York.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Selden applied for a patent for a car in 1879, but the patent application expired because the vehicle was never built.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] After a delay of 16 years and a series of attachments to his application, on 5 November 1895, Selden was granted a US patent (U.S. patent 549,160) for a two-stroke car engine, which hindered, more than encouraged, development of cars in the United States.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] His patent was challenged by Henry Ford and others, and overturned in 1911.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1893, the first running, petrol-driven American car was built and road-tested by the Duryea brothers of Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The first public run of the Duryea Motor Wagon took place on 21 September 1893, on Taylor Street in Metro Center Springfield.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Studebaker, subsidiary of a long-established wagon and coach manufacturer, started to build cars in 1897 and commenced sales of electric vehicles in 1902 and petrol vehicles in 1904.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In Britain, there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success, with Thomas Rickett even attempting a production run in 1860.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Santler from Malvern is recognised by the Veteran Car Club of Great Britain as having made the first petrol-driven car in the country in 1894, followed by Frederick William Lanchester in 1895, but these were both one-offs.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The first production vehicles in Great Britain came from the Daimler Company, a company founded by Harry J.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Lawson in 1896, after purchasing the right to use the name of the engines.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Lawson's company made its first car in 1897, and they bore the name Daimler.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1892, German engineer Rudolf Diesel was granted a patent for a "New Rational Combustion Engine".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1897, he built the first diesel engine.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Steam-, electric-, and petrol-driven vehicles competed for a few decades, with petrol internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design, only Mazda's version of the Wankel engine has had more than very limited success.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] All in all, it is estimated that over 100,000 patents have contributed to the modern automobile and motorcycle.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Large-scale, production-line manufacturing of affordable cars was started by Ransom Olds in 1901 at his Oldsmobile factory in Lansing, Michigan, and based upon stationary assembly line techniques pioneered by Marc Isambard Brunel at the Portsmouth Block Mills, England, in 1802.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The assembly line style of mass production and interchangeable parts had been pioneered in the US by Thomas Blanchard in 1821, at the Springfield Armory in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] This concept was greatly expanded by Henry Ford, beginning in 1913 with the world's first *moving* assembly line for cars at the Highland Park Ford Plant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] As a result, Ford's cars came off the line in 15-minute intervals, much faster than previous methods, increasing productivity eightfold while using less labour (from 12.5 manhours to 1 hour 33 minutes).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] It was so successful, paint became a bottleneck.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Only Japan black would dry fast enough, forcing the company to drop the variety of colours available before 1913, until fast-drying Duco lacquer was developed in 1926.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] This is the source of Ford's apocryphal remark, "any color as long as it's black".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 1914, an assembly line worker could buy a Model T with four months' pay.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Ford's complex safety procedures—especially assigning each worker to a specific location rather than allowing them to roam—dramatically reduced injury rates.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The combination of high wages and high efficiency is called "Fordism" and was copied by most major industries.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The efficiency gains from the assembly line also coincided with the US's economic rise.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The assembly line forced workers to move at a certain pace with very repetitive motions, which led to more output per worker, while other countries used less productive methods.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In the automotive industry, its success was dominant and quickly spread worldwide, with the founding of Ford France and Ford Britain in 1911, Ford Denmark in 1923, and Ford Germany in 1925; in 1921, Citroën was the first native European manufacturer to adopt the production method.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Soon, companies had to have assembly lines or risk going bankrupt; by 1930, 250 companies that did not have assembly lines disappeared.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The development of automotive technology was rapid, due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Key developments included electric ignition and the electric self-starter (both by Charles Kettering, for the Cadillac Motor Company in 1910–1911), independent suspension, and four-wheel brakes.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Since the 1920s, nearly all cars have been mass-produced to meet market needs, so marketing plans have often heavily influenced car design.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company, called the General Motors Companion Make Program, so that buyers could "move up" as their fortunes improved.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Reflecting the rapid pace of change, makers shared parts with one another, resulting in lower costs across all price ranges.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Most British small-car assemblers, from Abbey to Xtra, had gone under.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Citroën did the same in France, coming to cars in 1919; between them and other cheap cars in reply such as Renault's 10CV and Peugeot's 5CV, they produced 550,000 cars in 1925, and Mors, Hurtu, and others could not compete.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Germany's first mass-manufactured car, the Opel 4PS *Laubfrosch* (Tree Frog), came off the line at Rüsselsheim in 1924, soon making Opel the top car builder in Germany, with 37.5 per cent of the market.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In Japan, car production was very limited before World War II.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Only a handful of companies produced vehicles in limited numbers, and these were small, three-wheeled for commercial use, like Daihatsu, or the result of partnerships with European companies, like Isuzu building the Wolseley A-9 in 1922.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Mitsubishi was also partnered with Fiat and built the Mitsubishi Model A based on a Fiat vehicle.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Toyota, Nissan, Suzuki, Mazda, and Honda began as companies producing non-automotive products before the war, then switched to car production in the 1950s.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Kiichiro Toyoda's decision to take Toyoda Loom Works into automobile manufacturing would eventually lead to the formation of Toyota Motor Corporation, the world's largest automobile manufacturer.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Subaru, meanwhile, was formed from a conglomerate of six companies that banded together as Fuji Heavy Industries, as a result of having been broken up under *keiretsu* legislation.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Most cars in use in the mid 2020s run on petrol burnt in an internal combustion engine (ICE).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Some cities ban older, more polluting petrol-driven cars, and some countries plan to ban sales in the future.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] However, some environmental groups say this phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles must be brought forward to limit climate change.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Production of petrol-fuelled cars peaked in 2017.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Other hydrocarbon fossil fuels also burnt by deflagration (rather than detonation) in ICE cars include diesel, autogas, and CNG.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Removal of fossil fuel subsidies, concerns about oil dependence, tightening environmental laws and restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions are propelling work on alternative power systems for cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] This includes hybrid vehicles, plug-in electric vehicles, and hydrogen vehicles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] As of 2025 one in four cars sold is electric but, despite rapid growth, less than one in twenty cars on the world's roads were fully electric and plug-in hybrid cars by the end of 2024.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Cars for racing or speed records have sometimes employed jet or rocket engines, but these are impractical for common use.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Oil consumption has increased rapidly in the 20th and 21st centuries because there are more cars; the 1980s oil glut even fuelled the sales of low-economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In almost all hybrid (even mild hybrid) and pure electric cars, regenerative braking recovers and returns to a battery some energy which would otherwise be wasted by friction brakes getting hot.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Although all cars must have friction brakes (front disc brakes and either disc or drum rear brakes) for emergency stops, regenerative braking improves efficiency, particularly in city driving.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Cars are equipped with controls for driving, passenger comfort, and safety, normally operated by a combination of feet and hands, and occasionally by voice in 21st-century cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] These controls include a steering wheel, pedals for operating the brakes and controlling the car's speed (and, in a manual transmission car, a clutch pedal), a shift lever or stick for changing gears, and several buttons and dials for turning on lights, ventilation, and other functions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Modern cars' controls are now standardised, such as the location of the accelerator and brake, but this was not always the case.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Controls are evolving in response to new technologies, for example, the electric car and the integration of mobile communications.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Some of the original controls are no longer required.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] For example, all cars once had controls for the choke valve, clutch, ignition timing, and a crank instead of an electric starter.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] However, new controls have also been added to vehicles, making them more complex.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] These include air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Another trend is the replacement of physical knobs and switches with secondary controls, such as touchscreen controls, such as BMW's *iDrive* and Ford's *MyFord Touch*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Another change is that while early cars' pedals were physically linked to the brake mechanism and throttle, in the early 2020s, cars have increasingly replaced these physical linkages with electronic controls.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] More costly upper-class and luxury cars are equipped with features earlier such as massage seats and collision avoidance systems.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Dedicated automotive fuses and circuit breakers prevent damage from electrical overload.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Cars are typically fitted with multiple types of lights.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Interior ceiling lights in the car are usually fitted for the driver and passengers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Some vehicles also have a boot light and, more rarely, an engine compartment light.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] During the late 20th and early 21st century, cars increased in weight due to batteries, modern steel safety cages, anti-lock brakes, airbags, and "more-powerful—if more efficient—engines" and, as of 2019, typically weigh between 1 and 3 tonnes (1.1 and 3.3 short tons; 0.98 and 2.95 long tons).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Heavier cars are safer for the driver from a crash perspective, but more dangerous for other vehicles and road users.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The weight of a car influences fuel consumption and performance, with more weight resulting in increased fuel consumption and decreased performance.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The Wuling Hongguang Mini EV, a typical city car, weighs about 700 kilograms (1,500 lb).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Heavier cars include SUVs and extended-length SUVs like the Suburban.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Some places tax heavier cars more: as well as improving pedestrian safety, this can encourage manufacturers to use materials such as recycled aluminium instead of steel.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] It has been suggested that one benefit of subsidising charging infrastructure is that cars can use lighter batteries.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Most cars are designed to carry multiple occupants, often with four or five seats.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Cars with five seats typically seat two passengers in the front and three in the rear.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Full-size cars and large sport utility vehicles can often carry six, seven, or more occupants, depending on seat arrangement.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] On the other hand, sports cars are most often designed with only two seats.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Utility vehicles like pickup trucks combine seating with extra cargo or utility functionality.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The differing needs for passenger capacity and their luggage or cargo space has resulted in the availability of a large variety of body styles to meet individual consumer requirements that include, among others, the sedan/saloon, hatchback, station wagon/estate, coupe, and minivan.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Mary Ward became one of the first documented car fatalities in 1869 in Parsonstown, Ireland, and Henry Bliss one of the US's first pedestrian car casualties in 1899 in New York City.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] There are now standard tests for safety in new cars, such as the Euro and US NCAP tests, and insurance-industry-backed tests by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] However, not all such tests consider the safety of people outside the car, such as drivers of other cars, pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Some countries are tightening safety regulations for new cars, for example to mandate data recorders and automated braking.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The costs of car usage, which may include the cost of: acquiring the vehicle, repairs and auto maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance, are weighed against the cost of the alternatives, and the value of the benefits—perceived and real—of vehicle usage.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The benefits may include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience, and emergency power.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Societal benefits may include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation, from car production and maintenance, transportation provision, societal wellbeing derived from leisure and travel opportunities, and revenue generation from the tax opportunities.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The ability of humans to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for the nature of societies.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Trucks' share of US vehicles produced has tripled since 1975.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Though vehicle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend toward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of greater fuel economy and reductions in pollution and carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per unit distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Car production and use have a large number of environmental impacts: it causes local air pollution plastic pollution and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions and climate change.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Cars and vans caused 10% of energy-related carbon dioxide emissions in 2022.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] As of 2023, electric cars produce about half the emissions over their lifetime as diesel and petrol cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] This is set to improve as countries produce more of their electricity from low-carbon sources.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Cars consume almost a quarter of world oil production as of 2019.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Cities planned around cars are often less dense, which leads to further emissions, as they are less walkable, for instance.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] A growing demand for large SUVs is driving up emissions from cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Cars are a major cause of air pollution, which stems from exhaust gas in diesel and petrol cars and from dust from brakes, tyres, and road wear.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Heavy metals and microplastics (from tyres) are also released into the environment, during production, use, and at the end of life.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Mining related to car manufacturing and oil spills both cause water pollution.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Animals and plants are often negatively affected by cars through habitat destruction and fragmentation caused by the road network, as well as pollution.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Animals are also killed every year on roads by cars, referred to as roadkill.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] More recent road developments are including significant environmental mitigation in their designs, such as green bridges (designed to allow wildlife crossings) and creating wildlife corridors.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Governments use fiscal policies, such as road tax, to discourage the purchase and use of more polluting cars; Vehicle emission standards ban the sale of new highly pollution cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Many countries plan to stop selling fossil cars altogether between 2025 and 2050.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Various cities have implemented low-emission zones, banning old fossil fuel and Amsterdam is planning to ban fossil fuel cars completely.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Some cities make it easier for people to choose other forms of transport, such as cycling.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Many Chinese cities limit licensing of fossil fuel cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Mass production of personal motor vehicles in the United States and other developed countries with extensive territories, such as Australia, Argentina, and France, vastly increased individual and group mobility and greatly expanded economic development in urban, suburban, exurban, and rural areas.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Growth in the popularity of cars and commuting has led to traffic congestion.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Moscow, Istanbul, Bogotá, Mexico City and São Paulo were the world's most congested cities in 2018 according to INRIX, a data analytics company.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In the United States, the transport divide and car dependency resulting from domination of car-based transport systems presents barriers to employment in low-income neighbourhoods, with many low-income individuals and families forced to run cars they cannot afford in order to maintain their income.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Dependency on automobiles by African Americans may result in exposure to the hazards of driving while black and other types of racial discrimination related to buying, financing and insuring them.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Air pollution from cars increases the risk of a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, respiratory infections and aggravated asthma.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Air pollution is also linked to global impacts on all aspects of sexual reproduction from male and female fertility to fetal development, birth outcomes, and long-term health of offspring.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Children are extra vulnerable to air pollution, as their bodies are still developing and air pollution in children is linked to the development of asthma, childhood cancer, and neurocognitive issues such as autism.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The growth in popularity of the car allowed cities to sprawl, therefore encouraging more travel by car, resulting in inactivity and obesity, which in turn can lead to increased risk of a variety of diseases.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] When places are designed around cars, children have fewer opportunities to go places by themselves and lose opportunities to become more independent.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Intensive development of conventional battery electric vehicles is continuing into the 2020s, for example lithium iron phosphate batteries are safer and cheaper.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Other car technologies that are under development include wireless charging.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Software is increasing and may have many new uses, for example automatically not hitting pedestrians.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] New materials which may replace steel car bodies include aluminium, fibreglass, carbon fibre, biocomposites, and carbon nanotubes.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Telematics technology is allowing more and more people to share cars, on a pay-as-you-go basis, through car share and carpool schemes.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Communication is also evolving due to connected car systems.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Microwave weapons which can disable cars are being tested.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Fully self-driving vehicles, also known as autonomous cars, already exist as robotaxis in some locations.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Laws for the regulation of self-driving cars will need updating before widespread deployment can happen.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Car-share arrangements and carpooling are also increasingly popular, in the US and Europe.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Services like car sharing offer residents to "share" a vehicle rather than own a car in already congested neighbourhoods.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The automotive industry designs, develops, manufactures, markets, and sells the world's motor vehicles, more than three-quarters of which are cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In 2020, there were 56 million cars manufactured worldwide, down from 67 million the previous year.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The automotive industry in China produces by far the most (20 million in 2020), followed by Japan (seven million), then Germany, South Korea, and India.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The largest market is China, followed by the US.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] There are around 1.644 billion cars in use worldwide as of January 2025; they burn over a trillion litres (0.26×10^12 US gal; 0.22×10^12 imp gal) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly, consuming about 50 exajoules (14,000 TWh) of energy.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The number of cars is increasing rapidly in China and India.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In the opinion of some, urban transport systems based around the car have proved unsustainable, consuming excessive energy, affecting the health of populations, and delivering a declining level of service despite increasing investment.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Many of these negative effects fall disproportionately on those social groups who are also least likely to own and drive cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The sustainable transport movement focuses on solutions to these problems.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] The car industry is also facing increasing competition from the public transport sector, as some people re-evaluate their use of private vehicles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] In July 2021, the European Commission introduced the "Fit for 55" legislation package, outlining crucial directives for the automotive sector's future.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] According to this package, by 2035, all newly sold cars in the European market must be Zero-emissions vehicles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Established alternatives for some aspects of car use include public transport such as busses, trolleybusses, trains, subways, tramways, light rail, cycling, and walking.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Bicycle sharing systems have been established in China and many European cities, including Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Similar programmes have been developed in large US cities.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Additional individual modes of transport, such as personal rapid transit could serve as an alternative to cars if they prove to be socially accepted.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] A study which checked the costs and the benefits of introducing Low Traffic Neighbourhood in London found the benefits overpass the costs approximately by 100 times in the first 20 years and the difference is growing over time.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] Motorsport is a sport involving high speed racing and drifting.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/automobile] It includes various racing series such as Formula One, IndyCar Series, NASCAR, World Rally Championship and MotoGP.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] There are many types of car body styles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] They vary depending on intended use, market position, location, and the era they were made.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Lightweight off-road vehicle with sparse bodywork.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Originally two- or four-wheeled carriages in the 19th and early 20th centuries pulled by one horse, the motorized buggies were developed in the 1960s and grew in popularity and diversity.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A convertible allows an open-air driving experience, with the ability to provide a roof when required.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Most convertible roofs are either a folding textile soft-top or a retractable metal roof.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Convertibles with a metal roof are sometimes called 'retractable hardtop', 'coupé convertible', or 'coupé cabriolet'.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Two-door car, seating up to four persons.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Some two-door cars have only two seats, thus **two-seaters**.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Type of SUV with a sloping roofline similar to fastback cars, That is often adopted to offer a styling advantage compared to standard SUVs.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Manufacturers often sell them as more premium models than their standard SUV counterparts.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Vehicle with a higher ground clearence and larger space, That is built in a unibody platform shared with standard cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Originally a North American term used for vehicles that blend characteristics between two types, it evolved to be a term for SUVs built in a unibody chassis, Even though the term SUV is used to refer both to crossovers and standard SUVs due to their visual similarities.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Car with a roofline that slopes continuously down at the back.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] The design features a single unbroken convex curve from the roof to the rear.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Used in the U.S. in the funeral industry to carry flowers for burial services.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Typically a coupé-style, forward-passenger compartment with an open well in the rear.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Car with a hatch-type rear door that is hinged at the roof and opens upwards.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] The term "hatchback" can also refer to that type of rear door, which is also used on several sports cars, SUVs, and large luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] The modification of a passenger car to provide a long cargo area for carrying a coffin or casket.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Hearses often have large glass panels for viewing the coffin.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A vehicle that combines characteristics and styling of a sedan with a higher ground clearance, Similar to a crossover.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A Kammback is a car where the rear slopes downwards before being abruptly cut off with a vertical or near vertical surface.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] This reduces the aerodynamic drag, improving the efficiency, while the stil keeping its traditional shape.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Variant of a hatchback where the roof line and the rear cargo door are more horizontal than vertical.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A luxury-type vehicle that is typically driven by a chauffeur with a partition between the driver's compartment and the passenger's compartment.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Limousines may also be stretched to provide more room in the rear passenger compartment.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] In some European usage, the word describes a regular four-door sedan body style.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Vehicle designed to transport passengers in the rear seating row(s) with reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Typically has a combined passenger and cargo area, a high roof, a flat floor, a sliding door for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] In Europe, some small minivans have been marketed as 'leisure activity vehicles'.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Car with a distinct rear section, With the back of the passenger compartment being in an angle to the top of what is generally the baggage compartment.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A cargo vehicle based upon passenger car chassis and typically has one row of seats with no side windows at the rear.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A panel van is smaller than a panel truck or cargo van and is often built on a car platform.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A panel truck is a larger version of the panel van and is often built on a heavier platform.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] In South Africa, a pickup truck is called a "bakkie".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] An open two-seat car with emphasis on sporting appearance or character.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Initially, an American term for a two-seat car with no weather protection, usage has spread internationally and has evolved to include two-seat convertibles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] These form separate compartments for engine, passenger, and cargo.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A sedan is called a "berlina" in Spanish and Italian, or a "berline" in French.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Initially, a horse-drawn vehicle used to carry shooting parties with their equipment and game; subsequently synonymous with station wagon / estate car; and in contemporary usage a three- or five-door wagon combining features of a station wagon and a coupé.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Type of vehicle that combines characteristics of a passenger car with a offroad vehicle, like higher ground clearence and four wheel drive.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Has a two-box design, a large cargo area, and a rear tailgate that is hinged to open for access to the cargo area.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] The body style is similar to a hatchback car; however, station wagons are longer and are more likely to have the roofline extended to the rear of the car (resulting in a vertical rear surface to the car) to maximize the cargo space.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] In French, a station wagon is called a "break".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A semi-convertible style used on some sports cars, featuring a fully removable soft or hard roof panel that leaves the A and B pillars in place on the car body.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Based on a passenger sedan chassis and has a cargo tray in the rear integrated with the passenger body (as opposed to a pickup truck, which has a separate cargo tray).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] In Australia, the term "ute" was originally used solely for coupé utility cars; however, in recent years, it has also been used for pickup trucks.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Has two rows of raised seats, similar to horse-drawn carriages; usually did not have front doors, a roof, or a windshield.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] The baquet ("bathtub") style was produced in the early 1900s in Europe.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Also a marketing term used on cars built in the United States in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Italian two-seat sports car with either an open-top or convertible roof.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] The term was originally used for lightweight open-top racing cars from the late 1940s through the 1950s.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Since the 1950s, the name barchetta ("little boat" in Italian) has been revived on several occasions, mostly for cars with convertible roofs that are not specifically intended for racing.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Italian sports coupé, typically with two seats but also including 2+2 cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A retractable textile roof, similar to a convertible/cabriolet.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] The difference is that where a convertible often has the B-pillar, C-pillar, and other bodywork removed, the cabrio-coach retains all bodywork to the top of the door frames and just replaces the roof skin with a retractable fabric panel.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Some modern cars, Like the Fiat 500 (2007), featured this body style.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] An external or open-topped driver's position and an enclosed compartment for passengers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Although the different terms may have once had specific meanings for certain car manufacturers or countries, the terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Some coupé de villes have the passengers separated from the driver in a fully enclosed compartment, while others have a canopy for the passengers and no partition between the driver and the passengers (therefore passengers enter the compartment via the driver's area).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Usually describes pillarless hardtops that are cars without a B-pillar often styled to give the appearance of a convertible.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Popular in the United States from the mid 1950s through the mid 1970s.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] It also refers to a separate top that is removable and made of metal or other hard material for sports cars or small SUVs.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A car where the rear passengers are covered by a convertible top.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Often the driver is separated from the rear passengers with a partition, as per a limousine.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] American luxury coupés and convertibles produced from 1952 to 2007.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] The cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] An open-roof automobile without any fixed weather protection, which was popular from the 1900s until the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] An open-topped roadster body and a rear cargo bed.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A light, inexpensive, open car with basic bodywork and no windshield, top, or doors.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Most runabouts had just a single row of seats, providing seating for two passengers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] Body style was a type of automobile body used from 1908 until the mid-1930s, which had a streamlined profile and a folding or detachable soft top.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] The design consists of a hood or bonnet line raised to be level with the car's waistline, resulting in a straight beltline from front to back.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] A style of open car built in the United States that seats four or more people.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/car-body-style] The style was popular from the early 1900s to the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] From 1951 to 1980 **Chrysler Australia Ltd** operated as a vehicle manufacturer, it was purchased by Mitsubishi in 1980 with vehicles continuing to be produced under the Chrysler brand until 1981 by Mitsubishi Motors Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Chrysler returned to the Australian market in 1994 with imported vehicles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Chrysler Australia Ltd was established in June 1951 when the Chrysler Corporation acquired Chrysler Dodge Distributors (Holdings) Pty Ltd, a company which had been formed in 1935 by 18 independent distributors.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] During the 1950s and 1960s, Chrysler made a substantial investment in Australian manufacturing facilities.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] It consolidated assembly from other state capitals to its expanding operations in Adelaide.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Vehicle production for Victoria, Tasmania and New South Wales was in Adelaide from 1953 with Perth and Brisbane assembly ceasing in 1954.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The company had several facilities at Finsbury in Adelaide's northwest.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The trim shop (car seats and interiors) and steel pressings (chassis components) produced components which were sent to Keswick for assembly.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Chrysler also had an aircraft division which manufactured components for Canberra bombers, Jindivik drones and Winjeel trainers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Chrysler recruited both local men and young single men from interstate to staff the growth.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Initially, Chrysler Australia assembled North American Chrysler passenger cars and trucks.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Its most popular car in the 1950s was the US sourced badge engineered trio: Plymouth Cranbrook, Dodge Kingsway and De Soto Diplomat, each based on the 1954 US Plymouth.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] A coupe utility variant was also developed by Chrysler Australia and this was marketed in nine different versions; the Plymouth Cranbrook, Savoy & Belvedere, the Dodge Kingsway Custom, Kingsway Crusader & Kingsway Coronet and the De Soto Diplomat Custom, Diplomat Regent & Diplomat Plaza.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The Plymouth sedan was a popular choice for taxicab usage however the rise in popularity of the Holden during this decade led to the decline of this range of cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] In 1957, Chrysler Australia consolidated each of the badge-engineered marques in one car—the Chrysler Royal.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] This was a facelifted version of the 1954 Plymouth that continued in production until 1963.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Starting life as a side-valve 6-cylinder manual, with 3-speed manual column gearchange, it was progressively modified, with the addition of US sourced engineering features such as power steering, the push button "Powerflite" automatic transmission and an OHV V8.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] On the styling front US "Forward Look" style tailfins were grafted on the rear of the car, while the front end gained dual (vertically stacked) headlights.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] These changes failed to arrest the slide in sales, as General Motors-Holden came to dominate the Australian market, and the Royal was viewed as being outmoded and expensive.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The saving grace for Chrysler at this time was the French Simca Aronde—a popular 4-cylinder compact car which Chrysler Australia assembled from CKD kits at its Forestville factory.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Local engineers developed an Aronde station wagon unique to Australia, with a then-novel wind-down rear window and tailgate.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] (Chrysler USA had acquired an interest in Simca in 1958, the basis for sourcing of this car).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The assembly and marketing of Simca Aronde and Vedette models by Chrysler Australia was announced on 1 July 1959.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] In both 1958 and 1959, Chrysler Australia released Plymouth Belvedere, Dodge Custom Royal and DeSoto Firesweep models which were imported from the US in CKD form and assembled at Chrysler's Adelaide facilities.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The Plymouth was fitted with a 318-cubic-inch V8 engine and the Dodge and de Soto models featured a 361-cubic-inch V8.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Assembly of the three models was discontinued in 1960 and they were replaced by a single model, the Dodge Phoenix, which was produced by Chrysler Australia through to 1973.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] In 1964, Chrysler opened its Tonsley Park assembly plant located in the Adelaide suburb of Clovelly Park.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] An engine manufacturing plant was opened at Lonsdale in November 1967.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] These new factories replaced facilities at Keswick, Mile End and Finsbury.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] During this time, Chrysler Australia established its position as the third of the "Big 3" Australian motor manufacturers behind Holden and Ford Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Beginning in 1962, Chrysler Australia assembled the American Plymouth Valiant, marketed as the Valiant by Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] By 1963, they had developed a local version, the AP5 Valiant, with distinctive styling giving the car a separate identity from the US Plymouth and Dodge variants.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The reason for developing different styling was concern that the local manufacturer could not afford to make substantial styling changes as quickly as in the US.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Hence, a modified appearance would minimise the risk of accusations that Australia was selling "last year's model".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Through the 1960s, Chrysler expanded the Valiant range, with 2-door hardtop, long wheelbase (VIP) and sporty (Pacer) variants.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Also, in 1966, with the Chrysler USA acquisition of the British Rootes Group, Chrysler Australia took over the Rootes Australia as well as the operation of their Port Melbourne factory.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The principal Rootes model sold in Australia was the Hillman Hunter and this car became a steady seller for Chrysler until 1973.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] In 1970, they introduced the unique-to-Australia "Hemi" 6-cylinder engine—launched with an endorsement from Stirling Moss.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Billed as being "Right—for all the right reasons", this engine went on to become the most powerful 6-cylinder engine produced in Australia (equipped with triple Weber carburettors).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Though this engine was based on a US engine design for trucks, it was never produced in North America.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The Valiant was a good seller, but never quite gained the level of market acceptance as its major competitors—the Holden and the Falcon.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] In 1971, Chrysler Australia released the Valiant VH model (still based on the US A-Body platform), it was significantly wider than earlier Valiants, with the lineup including the memorable Valiant Charger.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] This was a short-wheelbase (105-inch) two-door hardtop version of the standard Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The car had distinctive sporty styling, including an integrated rear spoiler.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The base model Charger was A$2750, and the range extended upwards with high-performance and luxury models.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Charger won the "Wheels" magazine Car of the Year award in 1971.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] It was also a winner in the sales stakes, capturing the imagination of the Australian public in the same way as the Ford Mustang did in the US and the Ford Capri did in the UK.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Valiant was increasingly perceived as being outmoded—notwithstanding a major facelift in 1971 (billed as an "all-new" model) with a new body surrounding the existing mechanicals—the styling rapidly dated compared with other new cars, and the body was only lightly facelifted in 1973 and 1975.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] A significant facelift in 1976 arrested the slide in sales, and the Valiant continued to sell steadily until 1981.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] In 1975, Chrysler introduced the Centura with a choice of a 2-litre (4-cylinder) and 3.5-litre or 4-litre (6-cylinder) engines, and two equipment levels, XL and GL.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] This was a medium-sized competitor for the Holden Torana and the Ford Cortina.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The 'KB' Centura was based on the European Chrysler 180 (which had been introduced in Europe in 1970), with facelifted front and rear styling (reputedly based on the intended design for a Sunbeam version of this car, which never reached production).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The launch of the Centura was delayed by several years as a result of embargoes placed on French imports, due to France conducting Pacific nuclear bomb tests, which impeded the supply of parts.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] By the time the car arrived in Australia, its appearance was dated and, as a result, the Centura did not generate significant market interest.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] A mild 'KC' Centura update in GL and GLX variants combined with a simplified choice of two versions of the 4-litre engine arrived in 1977, but the car then quietly disappeared from the market by the end of 1978.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Chrysler Australia's parent company began working closely with Mitsubishi Motors Corporation after they acquired a 15 percent interest in the company in 1971, with the result that Chrysler Australia began building the Mitsubishi-designed Chrysler Valiant Galant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The association with Mitsubishi also gave Chrysler Australia another winner—the 1977 Chrysler Sigma.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] With a range of 4-cylinder "Silent Shaft" engines, competitive pricing, "Japanese" style and the availability of a luxurious "SE" version, with optional leather trim (an innovative sales approach in its era), the Sigma marked Chrysler's sales comeback.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Sigma soon became market leader in its class.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] In 1979, Mitsubishi Motors Corporation and Mitsubishi Corporation each acquired a one sixth equity in Chrysler Australia and in April 1980 the two companies purchased the remaining shares in the company from the US Chrysler Corporation, which was in bailout negotiations with the US government.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The company name was changed to Mitsubishi Motors Australia Limited on 1 October 1980.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Mitsubishi continued to build the Valiant models with Chrysler badging until August 1981 and production of the Sigma range continued under the Mitsubishi name until 1987.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Colt, Magna, Verada and 380 models were subsequently produced before production of passenger vehicles was discontinued in March 2008.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The company continues to operate today as one of Australia's major importers of road vehicles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Chrysler returned to Australia in 1994, initially importing the Jeep Cherokee, then expanding the range to include the Chrysler Neon (discontinued in 2002) Grand Cherokee, Jeep Commander, PT Cruiser, Crossfire, 300C, Voyager and Dodge Caliber.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] Initially, the attraction of the Jeep range was "value for money" although the first cars became known for poor quality of construction.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] In the 2000s, a range of vehicles were imported from the United States, Canada, Mexico, and Austria.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The Chrysler 300C found a successful niche as an alternative to Australian prestige cars—generally extended-wheelbase versions of traditional Australian family cars—the Holden Statesman/Caprice and Ford Fairlane/LTD.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] In 2012, Chrysler Australia took over the distribution responsibilities for Alfa Romeo, Fiat and Fiat Commercial.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] In 2013, the RAM brand of trucks was introduced to the Australian market, converted locally by ASV, at the Holden Special Vehicles facility in Clayton, Victoria.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-australia] The Chrysler marque was withdrawn from the Australian market on 19 November 2021 as its only model, the Chrysler 300, has been discontinued.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-drifter] The **Chrysler Drifter** is a panel van and coupé utility produced by Chrysler Australia from 1977 to 1978.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-drifter] Chrysler Australia added a panel van to their Chrysler CL Valiant range in April 1977, and a few weeks later they introduced the "Drifter Pack" as an option on that body style.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-drifter] The Drifter Pack included a Chrysler Charger grille, quartz halogen high beam headlights, a sports steering wheel, radial ply tyres, styled wheels and special exterior paint and decal treatment with colour-coded bumpers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-drifter] The 4.3 litre Hemi 265 engine and a four speed floor shift manual transmission were standard on the Drifter.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-drifter] In spite of its option pack status, Chrysler marketed the model as the Chrysler Drifter without using the name "Valiant".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-drifter] The Drifter pack was also available on the Chrysler Valiant Utility, which was also marketed as the "Chrysler Drifter".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-drifter] The Drifter styles of the panel van and utility body ended when Chrysler Australia discontinued the CL series.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-drifter] The 1978 CM Valiant range did not include these styles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-drifter] The brief life of the Drifter was marked by low sales, as competition from comparable offerings from Ford and Holden was stiff.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-drifter] Chrysler Australia also used the Drifter name on a special edition Charger Drifter, released in 1978.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The **Chrysler Valiant (VK)** is an automobile which was produced by Chrysler Australia from October 1975 to October 1976.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] It was the eleventh Australian produced Chrysler Valiant series.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The Chrysler Valiant VK series was introduced in October 1975, replacing the Valiant VJ series.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The VK was essentially a facelift of the VJ with revised grilles, taillights and badging.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The VK was intended to have significantly different styling to the VJ, however this did not eventuate due to financial constraints.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The range was rationalised with a reduced number of models and options.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The Chrysler name was now promoted more strongly with Chrysler badging displayed prominently on the new models.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The Charger was now known as the *Chrysler Charger*, having previously been promoted as the *Valiant Charger by Chrysler*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The six cylinder engines were fitted with a new Carter carburetor.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] A vacuum operated “Fuel Pacer” was offered as an option, the device using a flashing light to assist the driver in avoiding fuel wastage.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] This light was initially on the right-hand guard, but was later fitted to the instrument panel.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] Additional safety features included a pressure proportioning valve in the rear brake circuit, power-boosted brakes and hazard warning lights.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] Indicator, headlight dipping, headlight flashing and windscreen wiper controls were now housed in a steering column stalk.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] This was the first multi-purpose stalk control to be fitted by any of the “big three" manufacturers, the other two being Ford and Holden.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] 200 Charger White Knight Specials were produced, based on the Charger XL.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] Specified via Option Code A50, 100 examples were produced in Arctic White and 100 in Amarante Red.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] 3 speed manual, 4 speed manual and 3 speed automatic transmissions were offered.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] As of July 1976, the 215 and 360 engines were dropped from the lineup, to conform with ADR27A emissions requirements.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The 215 was replaced by a low compression version of the 245.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] VK production comprised 11,722 sedans, 4,039 wagons, 1,625 Chargers and 3,169 utilities for a total of 20,555 units.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] This was the lowest Valiant production since the S Series.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The VK was superseded by the Chrysler Valiant (CL) in November 1976.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] Chrysler Australia also produced the related Chrysler CK series, a long wheelbase, luxury model developed from the Valiant VK.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] In July 1976, the 360 (5.9L) engine was dropped to meet ADR27A emissions requirements, being replaced by the 318 (5.2L) engine as standard fitment to the Chrysler, which gained colour coded hubcaps and Cloth Cord trim at the same time.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant-vk] The Chrysler CK was replaced by the Chrysler Regal SE in October 1976, the later being the prestige model in the newly released Chrysler Valiant (CL) range.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The **Chrysler Valiant** is a full-size car which was sold by Chrysler Australia between 1962 and 1981.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Initially a rebadged locally assembled Plymouth Valiant from the United States, from the second generation launched in 1963, the Valiant was fully manufactured in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] It was sold locally but also in New Zealand and South Africa, with smaller numbers also exported to South-East Asia and the United Kingdom.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Parent company Chrysler made a substantial investment in Australian manufacturing facilities by establishing operations in South Australia with an assembly plant at Tonsley Park in 1964 and an engine foundry at Lonsdale in 1968.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Valiant thus established its position as the third of the "Big 3" Australian-made vehicles behind the Holden Kingswood and Ford Falcon.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Australian Valiant was built on the North American A-body platform but with many parts and components from Australian suppliers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Apart from a sedan and wagon body style, 1965 saw the introduction of a commercial utility that was badged the **Wayfarer** and later exported to South Africa as the **Rustler**.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Greater differentiation from the donor car crept in over time, particularly since the VE series, which was embraced by the Australian motoring press and won the 1967 *Wheels* magazine Car of the Year award.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The VF series of 1969 and the VG of 1970 departed even further from its North American donor both in terms of styling and performance—with the latter series introducing the *Hemi-6* engine that replaced the *Slant-6*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Moreover, Australia continued to produce a station wagon model, called the **Safari**, even after this body style was discontinued for North America.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Beginning in 1971, the VH series saw Chrysler Australia develop the entire lineup locally including the Charger.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Local design and production continued until the CM series of 1979, which marked the end of local production in 1981, after the takeover of operations by Mitsubishi Motors Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] After the Plymouth Valiant turned out to be a success in the United States (starting with its 1959 introduction), Chrysler released Australia's first locally assembled Valiant, the RV1 (R-series).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] It was officially unveiled by South Australia's Premier, Sir Thomas Playford, in January 1962 and was assembled at Chrysler's Mile End facility.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The RV1 (or R Series) Valiant was an instant success.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Not everyone was taken instantly by the car's styling, but the general consensus was that the car had a modern, almost space age quality about it.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Also notable was the Valiant's performance with 145 brake horsepower (108 kW) from the 225 *Slant-6* engine.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] This was a lot of power compared to the competing Holdens and Fords, which offered only 75 bhp (56 kW) and 90 bhp (67 kW) SAE respectively.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Standard transmission in the RV1 was a floor-shifted three-speed manual with a non-synchro first gear.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A button-operated three-speed TorqueFlite automatic was optional.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Other options included a heater-demister unit, as well as a "Moparmatic" deluxe pushbutton transistor radio.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The RV1 Valiant was the first Australian car to come with an alternator instead of a generator, and instead of coil springs, the Valiant came with torsion bar suspension.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Brakes were hydraulic 9" drums front and rear.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The RV1 had a simulated spare wheel outline on the bootlid, but the spare wheel was actually under the floor of the boot.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In March 1962, Chrysler replaced the American 1961-model R Valiant with the American 1962 SV1 (S Series) Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The SV1 used the same body shell as the RV1, with cosmetic changes including the deletion of the simulated spare wheel on the bootlid, and round tail lamps replacing the R-model's cat-eye shaped ones.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] There was a revised radiator grille and new exterior trim.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Mechanical changes included relocation of the manual transmission shifter to the steering column, new ball joints, and a new gear-reduction starter motor.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] 10,009 SV1 Valiants were sold, of which 5,496 were automatics and 4,513 were manuals.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] On 30 May 1963, Chrysler Australia produced the first fully Australian manufactured Valiant, the **AP5**.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In February of that year, Chrysler Australia had begun work on its new $36 million Tonsley Park facility in South Australia, where it could boost annual production to 50 thousand cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The new plant produced its first Valiants on 31 March 1964.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The AP5 ("AP" for *Australian Production*) was an entirely new design with only the four doors, windscreen, and front guards shared with its North American counterpart.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Initial cars retained the left-hand-drive wiper pattern but this was soon changed to a RHD layout.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The *Slant-6* driveline was retained, but the AP5 was considerably more straightforward in styling than its R- and S-model antecedents.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] With high local content and specifications optimised for local conditions, this new Valiant strengthened the brand's position in the marketplace.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A new upmarket **Regal** version was included in the range.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In November 1963 an AP5 **Safari** station wagon was released.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Total production of the AP5 range amounted to 49,440 vehicles.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In March 1965, the AP5 was supplanted by the **AP6**.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The body shell was the same, but there was a new grille on the theme of the 1964 North American Plymouth Barracuda, and there was new trim inside and out.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The automatic transmission was no longer controlled by pushbuttons, but instead by a conventional shift lever.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The AP6 also included other new features such as self-adjusting brakes and acrylic enamel paint, at the time the most advanced auto finish available.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The AP6 model range included the **Valiant Wayfarer**, the first Valiant-based coupe utility to be built by Chrysler Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The AP6 was the first Australian-built Valiant to be offered with a V8 engine – the 273 cu in (4.47 L) LA V8, introduced in American Valiants in 1964, and released in Australia in August 1965.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The engine developed 180 brake horsepower (130 kW) and pushed the Valiant to a top speed of 109 mph (175 km/h).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The V8 was only available as a model in its own right, the V8 Valiant, which had a vinyl-covered roof, individual bucket seats, floor console mounted automatic shift lever and two-tone steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The *Slant-6'*s camshaft was also slightly upgraded for improved torque by dint of increased duration and lift.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler Australia had difficulty meeting demand, with the Valiant being built at Tonsley Park at a maximum rate of 200 cars per eight-hour shift.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Customers had to wait up to four months for delivery of a new AP6.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The VC Valiant was introduced in March 1966 and, although underneath it was basically the same car as the preceding AP6 Series, the body was extensively restyled giving the illusion of being longer and lower.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The modern new design was highlighted by sharp, squared-off edges and corners clearly influenced by Chrysler in the United States.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The front now had a full-width horizontal grille while the rear was also much squarer with vertical taillights.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The range of models again consisted of the Valiant standard or Regal sedan, standard or Safari Regal wagon and Wayfarer utility.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] They featured higher standard equipment levels as well as new safety features, such as optional disc brakes on V8 models, which were named 'Valiant V8/Safari V8' and were essentially Regal models.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In total, Chrysler Australia built 65,634 VC Series models.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] This Valiant was an all-new design introduced in October 1967, based on the North American platform, which had a 108 in (2,700 mm) wheelbase.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The bonnet and guards were shared with the also-new 1967 North American Dodge Dart, with other styling cues otherwise inherited from the North American Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The car featured slightly larger body dimensions and greater interior space than the preceding VC Series.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The roofline was also flattened out and the rear window was given a concave profile.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Higher levels of standard equipment were featured and two engine options became available.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The basic *Slant-6* was retained with its 145 bhp (108 kW) rating, but a new 2-barrel carbureted version was released with output of 160 bhp (120 kW).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The 273 V8 was also improved and made available across the entire Valiant range.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] All models benefited from additional safety features (some compulsory under new Australian Design Rules, or ADRs) such as dual circuit brakes with a tandem master cylinder, double sided safety rims, front seat belts and front power disc brakes on V8 models.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The VE range consisted of Valiant & Valiant Regal sedans, Valiant Safari & Valiant Regal Safari station wagons and Valiant, Valiant Wayfarer & Dodge utilities, the latter being a lower-priced version of the Valiant utility.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The flagship model followed on from the AP6 and VC V8 theme, being similarly equipped with bucket seats, floor shift automatic, and vinyl roof all standard, but was given the new name "VIP" to distinguish it from other models, since the V8 engine option was made available across the range.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] It also shared the 3 'sergeant stripes' of the VC V8 on the rear quarter panel.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The biggest accolade for the VE Valiant was *Wheels* "Car of the Year" in 1967 – the first for Chrysler Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In March 1969, the VE was replaced by the **VF** model.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The new car shared its middle section with the previous VE Valiant, but there was new front and rear styling.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The new front end featured a horizontally convex grille, replacing the VE's concave design.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The front indicators were placed at the top leading edge of the front guards rather than in a more conventional location in the grille or front bumper.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] This allowed the VF's front bumper to be thinner and less prominent, which made the single round headlights look larger, and the front end appeared more aggressive as a result.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Valiant and Valiant Regal models were once again available, and the VF range also saw the introduction of the **Valiant Regal 770** and an upgraded VIP model.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The VF VIP was introduced two months after the Valiant range and was no longer a Valiant V.I.P. but was now marketed as a **Chrysler VIP**, in sedan form only.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] It offered a stretched (112 inches or 2,800 millimetres) wheelbase, with longer rear doors than the Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] As with previous model changes, the VF boasted even more safety features including a padded instrument panel and energy absorbing steering column.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A larger 5.2 L (318 cu in) version of the LA V8 replaced the 273, taking the V8's top speed to 109 mph (175 km/h).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Transmission options remained the same: three-speed manual or three-speed TorqueFlite automatic.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The most significant introduction to the VF range was the all new two-door Valiant Hardtop – essentially, a North American Dodge Dart coupé with the Australian Valiant front sheetmetal and interior trim.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] At over 5,000 mm (200 in), it is the longest coupe ever built in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Released six months after the other VF Valiants in September 1969, it was available in Valiant, Valiant Regal and Valiant Regal 770 models.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In mid 1969, Chrysler released a fast four-door named **Valiant Pacer**.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A low-cost, high-power version of the bread-and-butter Valiant sedan, the Pacer featured a high-performance six-cylinder engine and three-speed manual gearbox with floor shifter.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Despite a lack of exterior chrome, the VF Pacer stood out with its red and black grille, simulated-mag wheel hub caps, special body striping, 'Pacer 225' decals, and choice of "Wild Blue", "Wild Red", or "Wild Yellow" exterior colours.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The sparsely trimmed interior featured high back bucket seats, and distinctive black on white instrument dials with a dash-top-mounted tachometer.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Although lacking the V8 of its rivals, the Pacer could reach almost 180 km/h (112 mph) and, at $2798, was $400 cheaper than the base GTS Monaro.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Pacer was powered by a special version of the trusty 225 *Slant-6*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] With two-barrel carburettor, high-flow exhaust system, and 9.3:1 compression ratio, it produced 175 bhp (130 kW).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Standard brakes were finned, servo-assisted drum brakes all round, although most buyers opted for the optional front discs.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Underneath was Valiant's basic torsion bar suspension, lowered by 125 mm (5 in) to improve handling and with a front anti-sway bar fitted.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A 'Sure-Grip' limited-slip differential with either 3.23:1 or 2.92:1 ratios was optional.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Contemporary road testers were mostly full of praise for the Pacer, noting there were few cars that could match it on a performance for price basis.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] *Modern Motor* (May, 1969) took a VF Pacer sedan to 60 mph (97 km/h) in a respectable 10.5 seconds, the 1⁄4 mile (400 m) in 17.5 seconds and topped out at 111 mph (179 km/h).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In 1969, Chrysler's market share reached 13.7%.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In total, 52,944 VF Valiants were built.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] August 1970 saw the introduction of another facelifted version of the VE/VF bodystyle in the **VG** Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The VG's most noticeable difference was the use of rectangular headlamps instead of the traditional round ones (except on VIP models, which used quad round headlamps).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The guard-top indicator location was carried over from the VF.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The grille was a horizontal, single-plane item, and the taillamps were revised and wrapped around to the body side.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Sedan, Wagon, Ute and Hardtop body styles were offered once again as well as the same luxury levels as before.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The biggest announcement to come with the VG Valiant was of the all new *Hemi-6 engine*, replacing the *Slant-6*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The new engine was introduced as a 245 cu in (4.0 L) unit with quasi-hemispherical combustion chambers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The "*Hemi*" name was already legendary in America with Chrysler's use of the *Hemi V8*, hence Chrysler Australia's marketing leverage for its 6-cylinder offering.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The sporty Pacer sedan was available again, but whereas the VF Pacer was only offered with the one power output, the new VG Pacer offered 3 different versions of the new 245 *Hemi-6* engine, though Chrysler Australia didn't publish any power output figures for the Pacers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The standard Pacer had a 2-barrel carburettor and produced 185 bhp (138 kW).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] **Option E31** produced 195 bhp (145 kW) and included a two-barrel carburettor, higher-performance camshaft, smaller fan, and windage tray.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] **Option E35** included a 4-barrel carburettor, high-performance camshaft, heavy-duty engine bearings, a dual-plate clutch, torque-limiting engine mount strut, and the ordinary Pacer-spec transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The VG series Pacers were also the first and last to be offered in the Hardtop body style, of which three were optioned with the E31 package and three were optioned with E35 package.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] No VG Pacer Hardtops were available with the E34 option.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Due to Chrysler Australia's policy (local content law/government law) of using only locally produced components, and the unavailability of a local four-speed gearbox, the Pacer was offered with only a three-speed floor shift manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A total of 46,374 VG Valiants were built.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler released the VH Valiant range in June 1971.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The VH was designed by Chrysler in the United States with input from Australian engineers to be an Australia-only model range.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] It was a major change from the preceding VG range – these were larger cars, styled to look even larger than they were.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The grille treatment on the new VH range was a direct design descendant from the US Mopars with the central recessed area for grille and headlamps, surrounded by uninterrupted trim on the outer leading edge of the whole assembly.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The rectangular headlamps were carried over from the VG model.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The model range of the VH Valiant was quite extensive, starting with the new entry-level Valiant Ranger, and progressing to Valiant Ranger XL, Valiant Pacer, Valiant Regal, and Valiant Regal 770.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Carried over from the VG range, the basic *Hemi-6* 245ci engine was standard equipment for Ranger XL and Regal, but a new 265 cu in (4.3 L) version offered 203 bhp (151 kW) and was standard equipment for the Regal 770.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The *Fireball* 318 V8 engine was still an option, but only available on the Regal 770 sedan.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The basic Ranger sedan featured a new low compression *Hemi-6* 215ci engine that operated on Standard grade petrol.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] This engine was not available on the other sedan cars in the VH range.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Unlike the VG range, Valiant Pacer was now only available in 4-door sedan form.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Apart from vivid paint colours, optional bonnet blackouts and striping, the new Pacer featured a higher performance version of the 265ci engine, with 218 bhp (163 kW) at 4,800 rpm and 273 lbf⋅ft (370 N⋅m) at 3,000 rpm.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Pacer could run the quarter-mile in 15.9 seconds, get to 100 km/h in 7.6 seconds and reach a top speed of 185 km/h.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In fact, at its release, the VH Valiant Pacer set the record for being the fastest mass-produced four-door sedan with a six-cylinder engine manufactured in Australia, a record which stood for 17 years.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Pacer's days as the VH performance model were numbered, because that same year saw the announcement and introduction of what was to become Chrysler Australia's most recognised new car – the Valiant Charger.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In total, only 1,647 VH Valiant Pacer sedans were produced.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The new Valiant Charger was unlike anything that had come before and it had the Australian motoring press calling it, "...the most handsome car Chrysler has ever produced, and probably the best looking car ever produced by an Australian manufacturer".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A short-wheelbase, fastback coupe with an aggressive wedge-like stance, the Charger's design gave the effect of speed, even when it was standing still.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler's TV campaign for the Charger featured the young adults at whom it was targeted, waving at one as it swept by them and shouting "Hey, Charger!" One of the more memorable TV ads of the time, it created a cliché that haunts today's owners.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Charger won *Wheels* magazine's Car of the Year award for 1971 and was widely acclaimed by others in the motoring press, as well as the public.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Valiant Charger came in four model guises, closely mirroring the existing sedan range – Charger, Charger XL, Charger 770, and Charger R/T.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The first of the serious "track pack" R/T Chargers had option E38.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Despite being hampered by a three-speed gearbox, it still drew favourable comments from *Wheels*: "We achieved a time of 14.8 seconds for the quarter-mile – on smoother surfaces the Charger galloped away so easily that a best of 14.5 seconds is within reach".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Being a three-speed gearbox, these quarter-mile runs took only one gear change.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The most recognised performance Chargers were the **Six Pack** cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The term *six pack* denoted the triple side-draught Weber 2BBL carburettors with which the 265 *Hemi-6* engine – in option E37, option E38, and later option E49 – produced levels of power unheard of on a naturally aspirated six-cylinder at the time.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The triple carburettors also made for a distinctive throaty note when under acceleration.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] E38 versions of the Charger R/T featured a 265 *Hemi-6* which produced 280 bhp (209 kW) while the E37 was the street tune option made available on Charger 770 and Charger R/T.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] E38 was a race-ready Charger R/T with the additional A84 Track Pack option, which included a 35-imperial-gallon (160 L) fuel tank.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] There was also an A87 Track Pack option that included all the race track goodies, but for the larger fuel tank.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In mid-1972, the E38 option was superseded by the more powerful and greatly refined four-speed transmission E49 option.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] This drew comments from *Wheels* such as, "The raw quivering power is instantaneously on tap and with a ratio for every conceivable situation the Charger just storms through.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] It would take a Ferrari Daytona with racing driver Jackie Ickx at the wheel to stay with one".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] All E49s came with a Track Pack, 21 of which featured the huge fuel tank with dual fillers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The E49 six pack engine came with a baffled sump, tuned length headers, special shot-peened crankshaft, connecting rods, pistons, rings, cam, valve springs, a twin plate clutch and of course the triple 45 mm dual throat Weber carburetors.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler quoted this engine as producing 302 bhp (225 kW), with the car weighing 1,372 kg (3,025 lb).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The R/T E49 was the ultimate Valiant Charger, and with only 149 built the E49s are still widely considered today as one of the greatest Australian "muscle" cars ever produced.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Road tests of the era recorded quarter-mile times of between 14.1 and 14.5 seconds.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] This compares to times of 14.6 for the next quickest accelerating Australian muscle car, the Ford XY Falcon GT-HO (Phase III).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Although the Six Pack Chargers were the dominant performance players in the VH range, there was another Charger, the 275 bhp (205 kW), 340 cu in (5.6 L) V8 powered E55, that came close.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Option E55 was applied to the new Charger 770 SE in August 1972, and this car could reach 60 mph (97 km/h) in 7.2 seconds and complete the quarter-mile in 15.5 seconds – all topped off by a top speed of 122 mph (196 km/h).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A batch of several hundred VH Charger 770 318 V8s were exported to Japan along with CH sedans.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Chargers had a CH-like nose with VH sheet metal surrounding the CH four headlights and grille, a combination that NZ assembler Todd Motors would later use to create its unique VJ Valiant Regal 770 sedan.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Japanese cars also had air conditioning, side marker lights and separate white reversing lights as well as mirrors conforming to Japanese market regulations.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Overall, Chrysler Australia manufactured 67,800 VH Valiant cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] New Zealand distributor Todd Motors had assembled the Valiant sedan from CKD kits since the AP5, mostly following the Australian range though with fewer variants and engine choices plus local upholstery.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Regal 770 had the 265ci *Hemi-6*, floor-console automatic shifter, round dials with wood trim in place of the strip speedo and its own unique front bucket seats and trim.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The 318ci V8 was optional and a vinyl roof was standard but could be deleted to order.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Todd's sole locally built Charger model was also to '770' trim with the 265ci *Hemi-6* six and three-speed floor shift auto and did not have the bumper overriders standard in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Early runs had one-piece front door glass and hinged opening rear side windows but, due to problems with water leaks and excessive wind noise, this was soon changed to opening front quarterlights and fixed rear side glass.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Wagons were imported from Australia, to Australian specification.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] VH Valiants were assembled at Silverton, near Pretoria in South Africa using Australian bodies, electrics and trim and locally sourced mechanical components including a 225 cid engine.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Prior to 1971 South African Valiants had been sourced from Canada.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The VH model range also saw the introduction of the new luxury class vehicles, the **CH** range.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The CH was a further 4 inches (100 mm) longer in the wheelbase than the VH Valiant – 115 in (2,900 mm) – with a total length of 197 in (5,000 mm).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] It featured quad round headlamps and a different rear end treatment, and had quieter suspension and higher equipment levels.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The CH (or "Chrysler by Chrysler", as it is commonly referred to) was a four-door luxury model intended to compete with the Ford Fairlane and Holden's Statesman models in the luxury car market in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Also released in October 1971 was a two-door version of the CH which was called the Chrysler Hardtop, and shared the same wheelbase as the four-door Chrysler, along with the front and rear end treatment.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] May 1973 saw the introduction of the next model in the new All-Australian designed Valiant – The **VJ**.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Although essentially a facelifted version of the VH Valiant before it, the VJ's subtle changes made enough of an impact on the buying public to make it the biggest selling Chrysler Valiant model of all, with 90,865 units being sold.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Externally the VJ Valiant continued on with the VH series body styles, though the VJ reverted to single 7" round headlamps and a new 8-segment grille.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] VJ sedans also received new horizontal taillights.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Although the physical changes were few, many other new features were introduced in the VJ Valiant range, such as electronic ignition, rustproofing and floor-mounted shifters as standard features.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler upgraded equipment levels in July 1974 with front disc brakes, door reflectors, lockable glovebox and retractable seatbelts all as standard features.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] While the VJ range still offered sedan, wagon, ute, hardtop and coupe variants, the performance-oriented Pacer sedans and Charger R/T coupes were deleted from the new range.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] However, a variation of the E37 Six Pack engine (now with four-speed manual transmission) was made available, in the form of option E48, with most of the cars bearing this option ending up being base model VJ Charger coupes.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Four VJ Charger coupes were built by special order featuring the VH series option E49 engine.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The other carry-over performance variant was option E55, with the 340ci V8 engine option officially remaining as restricted to Charger 770 coupe application only.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In August 1974, a special run of 500 Sportsman coupes were released, based upon the Charger XL model.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] They were only available in Vintage Red with white body accents.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] These cars also had a unique white interior with plaid cloth seats and featured a standard 265 engine with a choice of either manual or automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In New Zealand, Todd Motors was even more adventurous with the VJ.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The base Ranger XL and Charger were updated, as in Australia, with similar NZ-only variations as the VH but the VJ Regal 770 was something of a 'parts bin special' and essentially a merger of a VJ Regal with a CH Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The nose – also used for several hundred VH Chargers built for the Japanese market – combined the CH's four headlamps and grille with VH Valiant sheetmetal (retaining the older, larger, clear park/indicator lamps) while the rest of the body was as per Australian VJ.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Inside, new front seats were CH style, with individual chairs forming a bench shape, and a column automatic shifter was now used.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Earlier cars had all-vinyl upholstery but cloth was fitted as standard later.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] New Zealand VJ Regals also had a vinyl roof in black or beige and the panel between the tail lights was also trimmed in vinyl to match – the vinyl trim could be deleted to order.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Chrysler was given a facelift in May 1973 to become the CJ Series.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The two-door hardtop was dropped leaving only the four-door sedan to carry on the fight against its Ford and Statesman luxury competitors.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The related Valiant hardtop's production continued.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In October 1975 the VK Valiant was released with few external changes from the previous VJ model.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger now had an argent version of the VJ Charger grille, the Charger XL had a white version and the Charger 770 also had the argent grille.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The VK Valiant Regal featured a "grille within a grille".
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger sedan, Regal sedan, and Charger all now shared the same tail-light treatment, using a horizontal layout with four chrome contours to keep air flow away and keep the lenses clean.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Chargers were not called Chrysler Valiant Chargers any longer; with the 'Valiant' name being dropped.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The VK Regal also had blinker repeaters housed in small chrome boxes which sat on top of both front guards.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Another unusual option was the **Fuel Pacer** option from the Chrysler US parts bin which detected low engine vacuum – as under hard acceleration – and illuminated the driver side guardtop blinker repeater to indicate wasteful driving.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Inertia-reel seatbelts and slightly different heater controls were introduced on the VK, as well as a combination control stalk for the lights and wipers from the Mitsubishi Galant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger also got full-length door trims, and carpet was now standard.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] VK six-cylinder series engines were the same as the VJ's, and the 245 *Hemi-6* now featured a two-barrel carburettor like the 265 variant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The V8s were mainly 318 cu in (5.2 L) units, though the 360 cu in (5.9 L) remained an option across the entire range.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] It was not very popular as the mid-1970s saw the trend towards smaller cars with smaller motors.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] While the "three on the tree" column shift manual gearbox was still available, it was rarely specified (although still popular on Utes) and the three-speed floor change was now gone too.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Buyers seeking floor-shift manual could choose the four-speed, which was available on all models but could only be had with a *Hemi-6*, not with a V8.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Late in the VK model run a limited edition Charger called the White Knight Special (option A50) was offered with a factory-fitted front air dam.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The changes were mainly cosmetic with running gear being largely stock.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] There were 200 White Knight Specials made – 100 Arctic White and 100 Amarante Red.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] 120 were automatics and 80 were four-speeds.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] 20,555 VK Valiants were produced and production ceased in June 1976.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] This was because ADR 27A for exhaust emission control became effective on 1 July 1976, and all the car manufacturers used that date as the introduction of a new model to comply with the new standard.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] VK assembly did not begin in New Zealand until nearly a year after Australian launch because a 60% sales tax levied on large engine cars, introduced during the 1973-4 oil crisis, drastically slowed VJ sales.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The model range in New Zealand was pared down to Regal and Regal 770 editions.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A version of the Regal was manufactured for the South African Police as the SPP package in the late 1970s which featured triple carburetors, an uprated gearbox, uprated differential, and larger disc brakes.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Chrysler was given a slight a facelift in October 1975 to become the **CK** series.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Production ceased just one year later in October 1976 when the Chrysler was replaced by the Chrysler Regal SE, a prestige version of the CL Series Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The CL Series Valiant was introduced in November 1976.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Although it used the same bodyshell as the previous VK range, the front and rear ends were restyled.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The front end used horizontally arrayed quad round headlamps flanking a central grille.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The front guards and bonnet were also reworked accordingly.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The new bootlid's curved leading edge flowed down to new taillights that sandwiched a simple centre garnish panel.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The bumpers, however, were the same units as had been used on the 1969 VF series Valiants.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger name was dropped; the base model CL was simply called *Valiant*, and the long-wheelbase "Chrysler by Chrysler" was replaced by the *Regal SE*.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The CL series Regal was marketed as the **Chrysler Regal**, in contrast to the Valiant Regal name used from the AP5 series through to the recently superseded VK Series.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The CL series was the last to include a Charger model, which – like the previous VK model – was badged and sold as a *Chrysler*, not as a *Valiant* submodel.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The CL Charger was generally available in only one trim level, the **Charger 770**, though a **Charger XL** was made available to police departments.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The CL series also saw the arrival of the panel van variant to compete with similar offerings from rival makers.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Interiors carried over largely unchanged from the VK range, though the Regal SE offered luxurious buttoned-leather seating as an option.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Base Valiants continued with the previous Ranger style strip speedometer, while the Regal dash featured recessed circular gauges and clock with a woodgrain finish.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Charger 770 dash was similar to that of the Regal, except it was finished in black and had a tachometer instead of a clock.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The 3.5 L (215 cu in) *Hemi-6* and 5.9 L (360 cu in) V8 were dropped, and the only engine options were low- and high-compression versions of the 4.0 L (245 cu in) *Hemi-6* and the 5.2 L (318 cu in) V8.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The CL's introduction had closely coincided with that of the strict exhaust emission regulations contained in ADR 27A.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] With the 318 engine, a new emissions control system was introduced: **Electronic Lean Burn**.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Transmission options were 3-speed manual with floor or column shift, four-speed manual with floor shift, and three-speed Torqueflite automatic with floor or column shift.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The automatic was standard equipment with the 318 V8, and optional with a 6-cylinder.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The 4-speed was optional for six- and eight-cylinder models.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The floor-shift auto option was fitted to most Regals and all Regal SE's.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In 1978 Chrysler released a limited edition run of 400 special **Regal Le Baron** models (option A17).
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Le Baron was available only in Silver, with red or blue interiors.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The 265 *Hemi-6* was standard, and the 318 V8 was optional.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Valiant and Regal sedans also benefited from the 1978 introduction of *Radial Tuned Suspension* in response to Holden's having marketed their suspension as particularly suited to radial tyres.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] RTS improved the car's handling and roadholding significantly, and "Modern Motor" magazine proclaimed that the Valiant offered a better drive than the Holden.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The last special option in the CL range was the $816 **Drifter** package, available on the Charger.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Drifter package included Impact Orange, Sundance Yellow, Spinnaker White or Harvest Gold body paint, and large side and rear stripes.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Drifters in white had additional "strobe stripes" on the bootlid.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Engine options were again the 265 six or 318 V8, but the 4-speed manual was the only transmission option.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A Drifter Pack was also offered on the Valiant Panel Van and on the Utility.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] 36,672 CL Valiants – including the last-ever Chargers – were built.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The CL was the last Valiant series assembled in New Zealand – by now the Chargers and Ranger were gone and the Regal and the Regal SE, replacing the 770, were the only models.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The Regal SE was the first car to be assembled in the country with standard air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The CM was released in November 1978, and was little changed bodywise from the CL model.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Only sedan and wagon models were produced.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A sports sedan called the GLX (option A16) was released as a replacement for the discontinued Charger and earlier the Pacer.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Its features included a Charger grill and dashboard, special cloth trim, Cheviot Hotwire mag wheels and black door frames.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] It was advertised as the car "For People Who Like Their Cars Rare", as it was the last of the sports models and the jewel in the CM series.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The GLX could be optioned with a 4.3 L (265 cu in) *Hemi-6* or 5.2 L (318 cu in) V8.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The computer-controlled Electronic Lean Burn system continued giving favourable fuel economy; when *Wheels* performed an economy test in 1979, they found the ELB-equipped Valiant 4.0 L (245 cu in) used less fuel than a 2.0 L (120 cu in) Ford Cortina.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A Valiant achieved better than 30 miles per imperial gallon (9.4 L/100 km) in the Total Oil Economy Run.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Production of this car continued after Mitsubishi's takeover of Chrysler's Australian operations.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Mitsubishi could build the car profitably even in small numbers due to its high 97% level of local Australian content and amortised tooling.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] However, the car was still badged as the *Chrysler* Valiant, not as a Mitsubishi.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The profit from the sale of one Valiant was equal to the profit from 3 Mitsubishi Sigmas- by this time the company's main seller.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Valiant production ended in August 1981 with production of the CM reaching 16,005 units out of 565,338 units of all models.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Eventually, the Mitsubishi Magna was developed to replace both the Sigma and Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Full-sized Chryslers were not marketed again in Australia until the 2005 release of the Chrysler 300C.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Although the Charger is arguably the best remembered Valiant in Australian motorsport, earlier models achieved class wins at the annual "Bathurst 500" production car race, something that the Charger never did.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] A Valiant AP5 won Class D at the 1963 Armstrong 500, a VC Valiant V8 won Class D at the 1966 Gallaher 500 and a VG Valiant Pacer won Class D at the 1970 Hardie-Ferodo 500.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Chargers were raced in the Hardie-Ferodo 500 at Bathurst in 1971 and 1972 with factory support.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] They gained a best placing of third outright and second in class in 1972.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler's policy was to race "Australian made" product, which meant the race cars ran 4.3 L (265 cu in) six-cylinder engines equipped with triple Weber carburettors and 3-speed gearboxes.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] Even skilled driving and good engineering could not defeat Ford's legendary Falcon GTHO Phase III with its 351 cu in (5.75 L) V8.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] In New Zealand, however, the Chryslers proved to be virtually unbeatable from 1971 to 1979 at the famous B&H 500-mile (later 1000 km) series at Pukekohe Park Raceway.
[src:chrysler-valiant-vk/chrysler-valiant] The most successful drivers were Leo Leonard and Jim Little, who still races his Valiants (mostly pre-65 class).
